H.T. Kirby-Smith's interesting post about the "irrationality" of rhyme as
a way of organizing poetic choices brings the discussion of chance
composition, in a way, to rhetoric.  Did anyone else see the piece in the
NYTimes about the susceptibility of the brain, to rhyme? In other words
there are reasons babies love to hear recitations of Dr. Suess.  (Lyric
as cry for Mama, as Barbara Johnson might say.)
 
I composed a long poem with a friend using dice.  We were delighted with
the results, but predictably maybe, no one was very interested in reading
the whole thing.  I mean the (inexistant) (?) metapoem was more
interesting than the poem, and we who did it were more excited than
anyone who read it.....
 
Please send aleatory energy to an 87 year old man you don't know, who's
about to undergo surgery....
 
Thanks everyone
Marisa
